Preheat broiler to high or oven to 500 degrees. Wash and dry all produce. Trim
ends from @zucchini{1}, then grate on the large holes of a #box grater{}.
Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} in a large pan over
medium-high heat (use an ovenproof pan if you have one). Add
@ground beef{10%ounce}, ½ TBSP @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon}, @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Cook, breaking meat up into pieces, until browned and cooked through,
~{5-7%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}. Wipe
out pan.

Heat another drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add zucchini and
scallion whites. Cook, stirring, until lightly browned and softened, about
~{5%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Turn off heat; transfer to plate
with beef. Wipe out pan.

Melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in same pan over medium-high heat. Stir in
@orzo pasta{6%ounce}. Toast, stirring often, until golden, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir
in @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @tomato paste{3%tablespoon},
@water{2 1/2%cups}, and remaining Italian seasoning. Bring to a boil and cook,
stirring occasionally, until orzo is al dente, about ~{10%minutes}.

> If mixture seems dry, stir in another ½ cup water.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup},
@Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup}, @olive oil{1/2%tablespoon}, salt, and pepper.
Drain any excess liquid from beef and zucchini; stir into pan with orzo. Stir in
@butter{1%tablespoon} until melted. Turn off heat. Season with salt and pepper.

> If your pan isn't ovenproof, transfer mixture now to a baking dish.

Sprinkle with panko mixture.

Place orzo under broiler (surface should be about 3 inches from flame). Broil
until panko is golden brown and cheese has melted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove from
oven, then scatter with scallion greens and divide between plates.

> This magical breadcrumb mixture could be sprinkled on just about anything and
> we'd happily dig in, no questions asked.